Camille Auer wanted to correct her gender, was diagnosed as mentally ill and now makes art on the subject - "A person should have the right to their own body"
Dozens of patient stories hang from the ceiling of the Academy of Fine Arts' Project room gallery.
Each of them says Camille Auer's name.
The papers tell a perennial story of how outsiders have written down their interpretation of Auer and his identity.
Decided for him who he is.
"I wanted to tell the person my point-by-point treatment history in order to make the violent nature of the process visible," Auer tells me.
By process, she refers to the gender reassignment process.
It's often a years-long study period that includes meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process begins with a referral to the "gender identity disorder" diagnostic studies conducted in Tampere and Helsinki.
For Auer, the process started four years ago.
Even before this, he had been using the estrogen he had ordered over the Internet and was very far along in his own repair process anyway.
She felt that she was a woman, but according to Finnish law, a person must go through a correction process in order to be legally correct.
Translaki, i.e. the Act on the Confirmation of Transsecual Sex (563/2002), obliges transgender people to undergo forced sterilisation in order to obtain the correct gender, for example, in the Population Register Centre and passport.
Currently, every person correcting their gender is required to have a psychiatric diagnosis and proof of inability to reproduce.
People have the right to decide about their own body.
"This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," says Auer.
The reform of the Finnish Translation Act has been discussed in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has issued eight observations on the law and the European Court of Human Rights has a precedent that obliges parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to respect self-determination.
The previous Finnish Government prepared the amendment to the Act under the leadership of the then Minister of Social Affairs and Health Susanne Huovinen.
There was an election and the True Finns entered the government.
Now the law change is stalled again.
We are talking about domestic political disputes that are not even related to this particular law.
"The government doesn't want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the government about changing the law," says Frank Johansson, executive director of Amnesty's Finland division.
The front of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One of them consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the medicines used by Auer.
In the patient record installation, any visitor can read, for example, the interpretation of Auer by a psychologist from Tampere University Hospital.
The psychologist met Camille Auer twice and based on these, wrote an account that would define Auer's right to treatment and help.
The student’s sense of reality appears vulnerable to vacillation.
The researcher’s perception of the self appears fragmented in a borderline way, and unstable personality traits are emphasised.
Auer did not identify himself from those descriptions.
"It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed as mentally ill," Auer says.
It was an even bigger shock when Auer was not granted gender reassignment treatment.
Medical staff said his resources were not sufficient to begin the process.
He was denied his own identity.
It was then, on February 11, 2015, that Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked the television in the transpol waiting lounge apart.
Later, a work of art called Monument for the Excluded emerged from that television, in which Auer reflected on his experience of power and how to use it.
"It's crazy that any person defined as female at birth can have their breasts enlarged, but to have their breasts removed, you need a diagnosis," Auer tells me.
Your body is not your own if you feel you are anything other than your sex at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer's experience is not the only one of its kind.
The gender reassignment process is tougher for many for mental reasons than purely medical operations.
Those who go through it meet dozens of people for whom you have to justify your own existence and right to your own gender experience.
"It's crazy that people who are in need of support and help are denied care, citing that their resources aren't enough," Auer says.
Many people who have applied for the process have mental symptoms behind them: depression, anxiety, possible bullying experiences.
On these grounds, the medical staff may decide that treatment cannot be started.
"Preventing treatment and getting help can plunge a person into an even worse situation than it was before the process began," Auer says.
Auer's personal exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
In the text of the exhibition publication, Auer writes: "I've had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life and it's a thing people tend to find difficult to digest".
Depression has been treated with medication and once Auer started taking hormones, I felt better.
He had finally been able to put into words the feelings that had existed in childhood and teenage years.
Why the broad jaw didn’t seem to fit your body and why your chest muscles had to be round instead of flat.
The most important thing for Auer has been that there are people close to him who can see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
"You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing up, using your voice and moving," she tells me.
Today, Auer already feels seen, she exists as a woman.
But early in the process, haphazard comments from loved ones could hurt a lot.
It hurts the most when loved ones misgender.
"They should know and they know who I am but they won't or won't be able to internalise it," he continues.
But not all trans people need physical changes.
They don't suffer from body dysphoria, or body conflict, in which the body or parts of it can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without the use of hormones and a long research process, one cannot get official confirmation of one’s own gender.
"There is absolutely no medical basis for these studies," Auer says.
And it's true.
In June 2014, the Danish Parliament approved a new procedure for the recognition of legal gender.
The new legislation is based on the right to self-determination regarding legal gender.
An adult applicant submits a written application for a new personal identity code stating that they feel they are of the other sex.
After the six-month reflection period, the applicant confirms his/her application in writing and the Ministry provides the applicant with a new personal identity code.
This right to self-determination is also demanded in Finland, and this demand is also summed up in Auer’s exhibition.
It has not been a therapy experience for the artist; the exhibition is a political and artistic collection of works.
I want to believe that art still carries weight and can bring about political change, at a time when politicians have forgotten about human rights.
