Civil rights group issues travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Civil Rights of African Americans (NAACP) has issued a travel warning for Missouri. The reason is the state's discriminatory practices and racist attacks there.
"The NAACP's travel release for Missouri will take effect on August 28, 2017, and calls on African American travelers, visitors and locals to pay close attention and exercise extreme caution when traveling in a state where numerous questionable race-based events have occurred recently," the organization's statement said.
A law that recently took effect in Missouri makes it harder to bring discrimination cases to court. In addition, the enforcement of state laws disproportionately targets minorities. The NAACP said these factors led to the issuing of the travel warning.
"People's civil rights are being violated.
They are stopped based on the color of their skin and assaulted or killed," Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP Missouri, told the Kansas City Star.
"We have not previously heard of as many cases in as short a time."
The Missouri travel bulletin is the organization's first warning for the U.S. state.
The organization cited racist comments against African-American students at the University of Missouri as examples, as well as the death of Tory Sanders, a 28-year-old black student from Tennessee.
Sanders died in questionable circumstances earlier this year. He was driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel. He was arrested by Missouri police, though he was not charged with a crime.
The travel briefing also pointed to a Missouri attorney general's report that found police are 75 percent more likely to stop a black driver than a white one.
"The purpose of the travel bulletin is to urge people to be on the lookout and warn their families, friends and colleagues of what may happen in Missouri," Chapel says.
"People need to prepare by, for example, including money for bail or telling relatives they plan to travel through the state."
According to the FBI, Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, the sixteenth most of any state in the United States.
The travel warning is also a response to Missouri's new law that makes it harder for companies to sue for discrimination in housing and employment.
The ACLU, an organization that defends civil rights guaranteed by the Constitution, recently issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after they passed immigration laws obliging police to arrest people for immigration violations. The organization says this increases racial profiling.
Generally, travel warnings are issued by the State Department and apply to other states. However, recently, NGOs have issued them in response to certain laws and developments in the United States.
