Sanctions immediately made talk tougher
Not so long ago, it seemed that U.S.-Russian relations were on their way from cold to warm.
On the sidelines of the G20 summit in Hamburg, U.S. President Donald Trump and Russian President Vladimir Putin seemed to get along just fine.
Since then, the atmosphere has cooled considerably.
There was a bitter reaction to the new economic sanctions passed by the US Congress last week and signed by Trump on Wednesday.
The most stunning response so far has been heard from Prime Minister Dmitry Medvedev, who says the sanctions bill signed by Trump amounts to a "full-blown trade war."
Even if the Russian reactions are dismissed only as escalations and excesses of political rhetoric, the escalation of tension between the United States and Russia is a fact of life after the brief post-Trump honeymoon.
In the United States, passing a sanctions bill on Russia, Iran and North Korea was not simple.
True, Congress passed the law with considerable unanimity, but for the president, it was reportedly considerably trickier to pass the law.
In fact, Trump recently criticized the law he signed as "significantly flawed."
President Trump's snarl must have been caused by Russia in particular, although the passing of a law restricting his own powers must also have been abhorrent.
As is well known, an investigation is underway in the United States into possible Russian interference in the presidential election as well as into the Trump campaign’s ties to Russia.
The strained relationship between the United States and Russia is a fact of life after a short honeymoon.
As the White House staff has changed frequently and various scandalous twists have been revealed to have been almost updated, it seems increasingly clear that foreign policy is not made in the United States under the leadership of the president but in spite of the president.
Such a situation is by no means desirable.
If the relationship with Russia is a gimmick in the United States, the same goes for the European Union.
In addition to economic sanctions, the tense security situation in the EU's core Baltic Sea region is straining relations.
The EU has given prominence to the situation in Ukraine in its relations with Russia and has called for the implementation of the Minsk Agreement.
Although the Union has so far remained united, at least on the surface, in its policy towards Russia, the interests of the Member States are quite different.
For a member state like Finland that does a lot of business with Russia, economic sanctions have been a real nuisance.
The implications of the recent US sanctions bill are still unclear.
There are fears that the sanctions will make it more difficult for many European companies.
In Finland, the impacts may be felt, for example, in the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline project and possibly in the Fennovoima nuclear power plant project.
Acidity in Europe has been caused by the exclusion of liquid natural gas, which is important for the US economy, for example.
Trade sanctions are a means in world politics to show disapproval.
However, economic sanctions must be well thought-out and scrupulous.
Otherwise, they can easily do more harm than good.
Is nothing sacred anymore?
The Trump White House now has the Statue of Liberty in its sights
Interfering with statues is the surest sign of a change in power.
The Americans know that as well as anyone: Iraqis, along with American soldiers, toppled a statue of Saddam Hussein in Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump administration's chief ideologues, knew well what he was doing in a heated argument with CNN's Jim Acosta. The Statue of Liberty was attacked by Miller in a word-of-mouth over the president's proposal to greatly reduce legal immigration.
Miller wasn't exactly criticizing the statue itself.
Had he done so, he would have been attacked by huge hordes of cruise organisers and figures impersonating the Statue of Liberty.
The object of his attack was the significance of the statue and, in particular, the addition of a poem by Emma Lazarus to the pedestal of the statue in 1903 – 17 years after the statue was completed.
Here's how Miller chimed in on Acosta: "I don't want to go into more detail about history now, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that lights up the whole world.
The poem was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller wasn't wrong, per se, but it's not just about history, as he said himself.
Essential are the poignant words of Lazarus, the only ones of their kind in which the state calls not just immigrants but "the poorest of the poor": "Your tired, your poor, / Your huddled masses yearning to breathe free, / The exhausted refuse of your teeming shore."
The poem is more relevant now than ever.
By no means did Miller engage in literary criticism. He made clear that "the poorest of the poor" are not welcome in Trump's United States.
The dispute over the meaning of the Statue of Liberty is part of a broader political and cultural dispute over the meaning of the United States.
After his death, Lazarus' friends campaigned for the poem to be affixed to the statue's pedestal. They knew full well that the act was strongly political.
The statue was intended to embody the links between French and American republicanism with a classical emblem, the feminine embodiment of freedom.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, but has a voice.
And it gives itself a new name: the mother of the deported.
Attaching the poem to the image was an ingenious feminist coup and a devastating attack on the American idea of nationhood.
Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, and the right has long wanted to change it back to the original.
Rush Limbaugh – a mouthpiece who can now be seen as some kind of omen for Trump – claimed in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty does not extend an invitation to anyone, but is an early frontrunner for neoconservatives to carry the torch of the United States into a world shrouded in darkness: “Lady Liberty steps up.
He is taking the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch will not show the way to the United States."
Rarely, Limbaugh was partly right.
The meaning of the Statue of Liberty depends entirely on perspective.
Lazarus saw it as the poor and exhausted but hopeful immigrants from the ship's deck after a long and trying journey.
He saw it from the perspective of people seeking shelter and a better life.
His Statue of Liberty is comforted by giving hope and welcoming.
And that is absolutely not what Miller and Trump want.
Their torch will not show the way but fan the flames of hatred, their only source of strength.
