Blocking critics on Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't handle criticism
The father of our country knew what bad publicity was.
Americans loved George Washington, but newspapers soon began to criticize him for everything from possible domestic politics to his political principles.
The criticism certainly irritated,
He did not silence his critics.
"If the freedom of speech is abolished, we may be led dumb and silent as sheep to the slaughter," Washington said in 1783.
Which brings us to Maryland Gov. Larry Hogan, who should learn from Washington.
Hogan's staff has removed at least 450 comments from his official Facebook page and blocked their presenters.
The American Civil Liberties Union sued Hogan earlier this week.
His staff considers the challenge unjustified, and the attitude was dismissive online as well.
"Who cares? This is just Facebook," many commented.
But it matters,
Especially in the case of Hogan.
Hogan is the stunningly popular Republican governor of a Democratic-controlled state.
He has received the second-best ratings among the 50 governors for his actions.
Hogan is not a responsive hothead.
He has run the state solidly and held firm to the principles.
He has also been able to use Facebook as the main channel of communication with his constituents, posting a photo of his bald head undergoing chemotherapy there.
That's why blocking users who come to the governor's Facebook page is unnecessary and even dangerous. The governor's page is a public and official forum maintained by his staff with tax funds.
Hogan's spokeswoman, Amelia Chasse, excused the governor's actions in an interview with The Washington Post. She said it was simply a matter of moderating comments.
However, branding commenters as trolls, spammers or haters is too easy a solution.
The Washington Post interviewed users who were blocked by Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to leaders of their choice. They were not trolls but teachers, entrepreneurs and pastors, for example.
They told me their comments were respectful, thoughtful and matter-of-fact.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his comment; he wanted to appeal to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Maryland, was not hostile but asked a question about hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that Hogan had not taken a stand on hate crimes and other recent news," he wrote in comments to the Washington Post news release.
"Nor can I accept that when more people comment on the same thing, they are immediately viewed as an organised bunch in some way and ignored as a large group of concerned citizens."
The governor's staff called the comments a "focused attack." Someone else might call them to advance issues considered important.
In the age of Facebook, it's easy to control communication by blocking a reviewer or deleting a critical comment.
In the old days, you would have had to send staff to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or arrest and silence protesters.
It’s the same thing, only digitally.
Hogan is not the first public officeholder to be accused of shackling Facebook and other social media channels.
He has been sued by Twitter users blocked by President Trump.
The issue was the subject of the first major ruling last week in Virginia.
Alexandria District Court Judge James C. Cacheris said the Loudoun County government violated the First Amendment of the U.S. Constitution by blocking a voter on Facebook.
And the American Civil Rights Union took a swipe at Kentucky's Republican governor, Matt Bevin, for using Twitter and Facebook.
This shouldn't be hard.
In Washington's day, low-cost postage had a similar effect to the Internet today.
The number of newspapers quadrupled from 1776 to 1800, and anonymous writers hammered Washington.
At that time there were trolls.
Nicknames Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius and Portius wrote letters to newspapers decrying Washington's decisions.
The president's office was flooded with petitions criticizing the Jay Agreement, a cooperation, trade and shipping agreement between the U.S. and Britain. This is evident from documents collected by the Papers of George Washington online project.
But he did not silence his critics.
Freedom of speech, freedom of opinion and freedom of debate are the foundation stones of our nation.
True leadership means accepting this fact.
