Poverty and death in Indonesia's gold country
Bardina Degei does not use a stove in cooking.
He also rarely uses pots.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in Indonesia's restive Papua province. When he prepares dinner, he usually puts the sweet potato – locally known as "nota" – right in the hearth.
After half an hour, the charred sweet potato is eaten voraciously with bare, unwashed hands.
Degei's home has no furniture. She sits on a muddy ground floor, where she usually also does her daily chores, such as doing laundry in murky water retrieved from a nearby swamp.
The toilet post is supplied by a bucket in a roofless room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband's four wives, and no fields have been assigned to her.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed, and many drink a lot. In addition, it is necessary to take into account the soldiers.
"No one dares to walk around the village after 5 in the evening," Degei tells me.
This is a rare peek into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed by Indonesia in 1969. The annexation was preceded by a controversial referendum that forced 1,026 village elders to vote in public before the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed Dutch rule, quickly turned its ire on the Jakarta government, which maintains tight control over the area and bars foreign journalists and human rights monitors from entering.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua. The eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is remote and bleak. The journey there begins with an hour-and-a-half flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and continues with a stomach-wrenching five-hour drive in a hire car.
There is no public transport here.
The town of about 19,000 has wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, with corrugated tin roofs stained yellow-brown by rust.
Few Indonesians have been here, let alone journalists and foreigners.
Before the advent of Christian missionaries, Papuan Mee Pago tribesmen worshipped the god Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We didn't have any clothes like this," Degei tells me. She means her colorful, hand-woven wrap-around headpiece, dark skirt and brightly colored blouse.
"Before, all we had were leaves to cover our bodies."
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province. Twenty-eight percent of its people live below the poverty line, and infant mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it is also Indonesia's gold country.
Paniai is a highland region roughly the size of New Jersey with 153,000 residents. Just about 100 kilometers from Paniai is Grasberg, the world's largest and most profitable gold mine. It is owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix in the United States.
In 2015, the mine produced $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has estimated timber reserves of $78 billion.
For Papuans, however, these riches bring misery, as they mean the stifling presence of Indonesia's strong military.
The New York Times revealed in 2005 that Freeport paid local military personnel and local Army units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004. Individual officers were paid up to $150,000.
Papua's demands for greater self-determination threaten this source of income, and are mercilessly silenced.
Human rights activists say the Indonesian military has killed more than 500,000 Papuans since 1969 and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, mass killings in Papua's tribal highlands in the 1970s took on genocidal proportions.
Last year, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in the area during peaceful protests.
The Brisbane Archdiocese’s 2016 report, We Will Lose Everything, contains accounts of previous year’s atrocities, including extrajudicial executions, torture – rape and electrocution are particularly popular methods – and relentless attacks on peaceful protests.
"It is difficult to calculate the number of victims because there are weekly cases," said Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia for Human Rights Watch.
The screw has been tightened as Papua's natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Eighty-three percent of the province's 3.5 million people are Christian, but the demographics are changing as Muslims from Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi migrate to the region for a better livelihood.
Javanese warung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado-gado vegetable mix in peanut sauce.
It's hard for locals to compete.
"Migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables at the market cheaper than the locals," says Abeth You, 24, a native of Paniai who moved to the provincial capital for work.
"Local women lost their customers".
In his 2014 election campaign, Indonesian President Joko Widodo – nicknamed Jokowi – pledged to address injustices and human rights abuses in Papua.
Papua is made up of 29 regions, and this former carpenter won the vote in 27 regions, including Paniai, on his way to Jakarta's presidential palace.
But little has changed in Papua, and locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts were broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 and waited for him to fulfill our wishes and restore justice," You says.
Paniai experienced something of a trough just two months after Jokowi's October inauguration.
Eleven children were singing Christmas carols by the fire in Enarotal on 7 December 2014 when two Indonesian soldiers appeared from the dark on motorcycles.
The frightened children told the soldiers they should use their headlights.
One of the soldiers did not like the remark. According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, the man returned to the scene with four soldiers.
