In 1946, Black people in the state of Georgia were allowed by the Supreme Court to vote in presidential elections for the first time. The Supreme Court issued its decision in April, and elections were held in the summer.
The FBI said there was an incident around the election in which a Black tenant farmer, Roger Malcom, stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, in a fight apparently involving Malcom's wife, Dorothy.
Brooks said there were rumors in town that Hester had been having an affair with Dorothy and that Dorothy was pregnant with her child.
According to FBI records, on July 25, 1946, powerful white landowner Loy Harrison posted Malcom's $600 bail, against which he was released from prison.
On the way home, Malcom and Dorothy were joined by their cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
The crowd stopped their car before the Moore's Ford Bridge.
"It turns out that Harrison ordered and orchestrated the murders," the FBI debrief states.
"It is also apparent that there was collusion between state and local authorities. Authorities were involved in the murders and disposed of the evidence and did not reveal the identity of the witnesses."
Brooks puts it more succinctly.
"It was a voting rights murder," he says.
"They were murdered because they wanted to signal to black people that the same thing would happen to them if they were going to vote."
Cassandra Greene has directed the re-enactment of the Georgia massacre for nearly a decade.
