Rascona, or Hester, responds.
And then there's the punch.
And then everyone (at least all black actors) bursts out laughing.
Greene laughs the loudest.
"What?!" Rascona asks.
He's confused.
"Did I accidentally hit you too hard?" he asks.
"No," Greene fumes.
"I just don't think white people at the time used the word n---u."
"Yeah," another black actor confirms.
"It's slang. You have to use a longer version."
The subject matter of the show is unpleasant, but the room is taken over by a spirit of friends.
Everyone wants to succeed, and not just for show, but to honor the memory of those who were killed.
The scene starts all over again.
Now Rascona's words smite.
Nobody's laughing.
The recasting will end quickly and violently.
Screaming, gunshots, and silence.
A woman dressed in black funeral attire stands by the bodies and sings Billie Holiday's Strange Fruit.
His voice breaks at every other word.
A few hundred feet away, some 50 spectators are wiping sweat and tears from their eyes.
Almost half of the audience is black and half is white.
Among them are a couple who have come to see a show from Ithaca in New York State, but most are locals.
They have visited, with Brooks' guidance, the graves of the victims in the oppressive humidity of Georgia.
The murders have gone from story to reality, the mood at the scene is heavy.
After the singing performance, Greene invites the crowd to inspect the bodies.
Children squat to look at fake blood and motionless bodies and whisper to each other.
"They're not really dead," the little boy mutters as if to remind himself.
After a few minutes, Greene thanks the audience.
The actors who played the lynchpins take off their capes and wipe away tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, the man who played the local Ku Klux Klan leader.
Nick Rascona hugs two actors and then bursts into tears after a rough performance.
