Results of Swedish asylum seeker age tests published
The latest results of the Swedish medical age tests for asylum seekers have been published. The results of the tests carried out using the new assessment method reveal that more than 80 per cent of those tested were determined to be over 18 years of age. However, not everyone regards the tests as reliable.
Sweden's national forensics agency began testing earlier this year.
The new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for failing to determine the actual age of applicants claiming to be minors.
The Immigration Department has commissioned 6,880 tests so far, and the Bureau of Forensic Science has now released the results of 2,481 tests. The tests were conducted between mid-March and late July in 2017.
Eighty per cent of those tested, or 2002 asylum seekers, were determined to be over 18. In addition, the Bureau of Forensic Medicine determined in 25 cases that the person being tested was "possibly 18 or older."
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker is "possibly under the age of 18."
Tests were only carried out in cases where there was reason to doubt the age indicated by the applicant.
Johan Göransson from the Bureau of Forensic Science says the results are consistent with those of previous months.
"The numbers are pretty consistent. There are no big differences from the statistics from previous months," he told The Local.
Although a large proportion of applicants were determined to be over 18, it does not necessarily mean that applicants lied about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests and reported that there were "indications that the subject is 18 or older" in 442 cases.
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it emerged that in 243 cases the applicant had openly stated that he would turn 18 this year.
The medical age assessment method used in the tests takes X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRIs of knee joints. Then dentists and radiologists analyze the images. The method has also been criticized.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institute, whose work includes assessing people's biological maturity. The assessment can be used to determine whether a person has reached puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I've had reason to think about it and I don't think the method used is the right one.
Determining biological age in this way is highly uncertain.
If we can't definitely determine the age, we shouldn't pretend we can do it," he said to the Metro newspaper.
But Göransson, of the Bureau of Forensic Science, excused the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of determining a child as an adult is low.
The risk is highest in a situation where the test subject turns 18 years of age. The risk is then about 10 per cent."
