UEFA introduced the Fair Play Financial Rules in 2011, which state that PSG must be able to demonstrate that Neymar's transfer has been funded without major losses.
Barcelona were paid 222 million euros to end the Brazilian's contract, and Neymar's annual salary at the new club moves in the tens of millions of dollars.
There are a wide range of financial considerations surrounding Neymar's transfer to France.
PSG will have no trouble paying Neymar's transfer fee and adding him to their star roster, as the club is funded by the Qatari oil-rich dynasty.
Clubs are allowed to spend large sums to acquire players, but they need to be balanced with real sources of revenue so that football-related business is not loss-making.
Fair play financial rules were drawn up at the initiative of Michel Platini, the Frenchman who was elected UEFA president in 2007.
As a former footballer, Platini felt that pursuing success through debt was cheating and led to serious problems if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, the focus of fair play financial rules shifted from clubs" debts to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that implementation of the business model first used by Roman Abramovich at Chelsea in 2003 was significantly hampered. Abramovich bought a promising team, spent huge sums on player acquisitions and created a global brand.
The current three-year assessment period for Fairplay's financial rules runs until 2018. During that period, clubs are allowed to make a maximum of €30m in losses.
Although Platini was forced to step down as UEFA president in a scandalous 2015, his successor Aleksander Ceferin also wants to curb the reckless spending of clubs.
"The rules of fair play are still in place, and we will continue to apply them in the future," Andrea Traverso, who is in charge of fair play financial rules at UEFA, told The Associated Press news agency last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar out of his contract in a lump sum, it can amortise the amount in the accounts for the full duration of his new contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so the transfer amount can be booked as an annual cost of €44.4 million for the next five years.
The first sanctions were handed out on the basis of fair play financial rules in 2014. The biggest sanctions were imposed on PSG and Manchester City, which is financed from Abu Dhabi.
PSG received a fine of 60 million euros, which was later reduced to 20 million euros. The club was also ordered to limit its Champions League group to 21 players for the 2014-2015 season instead of the usual 25.
UEFA is monitoring clubs that may try to circumvent its financial regulations by increasing their revenues through companies linked to club owners.
For example, if a Qatari company subsidises PSG but the value of the aid is considered to be above normal market levels, UEFA will not calculate the aid as actual revenue.
That was the case when UEFA ruled in 2014 that the Qatar Tourism Authority's support for PSG was overdone.
Reports have also emerged that some of Neymar's earnings at PSG might be funded by payments from Qatar's 2022 football World Cup organising committee.
But PSG and the organising committee have denied that Neymar is being made an ambassador for the World Cup. It would be very easy for UEFA to reveal such an arrangement.
Given PSG's previous sanctions, UEFA will be watching even more closely than usual attempts to skirt the rules.
Sources with knowledge of the situation said on Thursday that UEFA were not in talks with PSG over a move for Neymar.
The sources gave an interview to the Associated Press news agency on condition that their identities not be disclosed because they are not authorized to discuss PSG's situation.
According to the latest published financial statements, PSG’s net sales for the period 2015-2016 were EUR 542.4 million and operating profit was over EUR 10 million.
Last season's financial statements have not yet been released.
PSG expects Neymar's arrival to attract new sponsors and boost sales of club products and jerseys.
The club estimates that its turnover will increase by at least 30 per cent with the Neymar deal.
A clearly irritated by the departure of one of the world's best players, the Spanish league tried to make it difficult for Neymar to make the move. It was alleged to breach the financial rules of fair play.
"This is a clear financial doping case both for the club and the state," Spanish league president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS. At the state, he was referring to PSG's Qatari ownership.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger also has reservations about the state funding the football club. Arsenal is owned by an American sports tycoon.
"The incident is the result of ownership that has completely changed the environment in which football operates over the last 15 years," Wenger said on Thursday.
"Anything is possible after the government owns a football team.
Complying with the financial rules of fair play becomes very difficult. There are so many different interests involved in having a famous player representing the state."
