Small-circuit nostalgia: Wet Hot American Summer and Comrade Detective
The story spans both the glory days of the 80s and the grunge of the 90s (in those days, David Wain and Michael Showalter were doing a great sketch show for MTV) and their own time – 2001, before Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler, Paul Rudd and the other stars of the show moved on to bigger things in their careers.
As a cultural product, it's both a parody and a description of the constant reminiscence we're stuck in in the Facebook era.
As a commercial product, it feels out of date.
First Day of Camp worked surprisingly well, and not only because of its absurd humor (it told, among other things, the backstory of a vegetable can speaking in the voice of H. Jon Benjamin).
The gist of the joke is that middle-aged actors play lusty teenagers approaching adulthood. Highlighting it makes the impossibility of reaching for the past part of the joke.
Ten Years Later, in which adults play adults, is less emotion-based, and its parody is more disjointed: it parodies 90s stalker flicks, for example, such as the horror film The Hand That Rocks the Cradle.
At one point, one of the characters unearths an Apple Powerbook, inline roller skates and "other stuff from 1991."
Many of the stories are the same as before.
The kind-hearted Coop (Michael Showalter) is now a writer but is still not over Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) is still a virgin.
And one wacky plot involves Ronald Reagan (as well as Michael Showalter) as his partner in crime, George H.W. Bush (played aptly by Michael Ian Black).
As always in such series, the best are the side paths.
It's particularly fun to see the ever-young Paul Rudd with a beard tuft under his lower lip, aka Matt Dillon's "soul patch" from Singles. Played by Rudd, Andy, the camp kingpin, is getting old geezer.
Moments of random madness may put this series on the air as a kind of recursive Seven Up! until it reaches its apparent conclusion: Wet Hot American Summer – Twenty Years Later. In its final scene, a group of friends go to the premiere of Wet Hot American Summer.
Amazon's "Comrade Detective" series, on the other hand, invokes a different kind of nostalgia: the Cold War spirit of "The Americans," "Atomic Blonde" and even the wrestling imagery of the GLOW series, where East meets West.
Created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka, the comedy series is directed by Rhys Thomas. It's made into a Romanian 1980s police drama in which a pair of Bukarestian cops fight for truth, atheism and Marxism-Leninism.
Starring as tough-guy Gregor and idealistic Iosef are Florin Piersic Jr and Corneliu Ulici. Their lines have been dubbed into English by Channing Tatum (the show's lead producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
It's a great idea,
But much else it is not.
The show has some good visual jokes (cops spend time watching chess on TV the same way Americans watch football).
There are a number of famous voice actors, including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloë Sevigny.
However, the Commodore Detective gets too caught up in imitating clumsy socialist drama – there’s a killer hiding behind a Reagan mask, for example. That’s why the show often starts to feel like clumsy propaganda.
The six long episodes are too long, and the show's humor is neither fast nor plentiful enough.
In summary, the show might work better as an agitprop satire, say, when Gregor and Iosef repeatedly visit the US embassy and there are always two fat men gorging on burgers in the lobby.
The message to an imagined communist audience is that Western culture can turn everything into consumer goods and fast food.
The show's fictional Romanian creators weren't wrong: we were numbly devouring our own recent history and theirs, too.
