Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25 percent
The Bank of England is expected to announce that it will keep interest rates unchanged after a lacklustre economic growth and easing inflation has ended speculation about rate hikes.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will continue to be slow. The Bank moved rate hikes because of increased pressure on families" income levels.
The decision-makers of the central bank’s monetary policy committee voted 6-2 to keep interest rates at 0.25%. This month the increase received even less support due to the lack of economic growth.
In its quarterly inflation review, the Bank lowered its 2017 growth forecast to 1.7% and its 2018 forecast to 1.6%. It also warned that household incomes will come under even more pressure as inflation is still expected to pick up to close to 3% in the autumn.
However, the Bank said that interest rate hikes will be needed over the next few years to curb inflation fuelled by Brexit. In addition, the Bank indicated that borrowing costs may have to be increased by more than expected in financial markets.
In addition, members of the commission decided to cancel part of a massive economic package that began to be implemented a year ago in the aftermath of the Brexit referendum.
The bank will end the Term Funding Scheme in February 2018, although it is now expected to provide £15m more, or £115m in total, to banks through the programme.
The minutes of the Bank's interest rate decision state: "The Monetary Policy Commission's forecast suggests that the slow pace of gross domestic product will continue over the next few years as lower real household incomes reduce consumption."
On interest rates, the Bank reiterated that a "some degree of tightening of monetary policy" was needed to curb inflation "a little more broadly" than market expectations.
The market is currently forecasting the first increase in the third quarter of 2018 and the second in 2020.
However, the bank stressed that any increases will be "gradual" and "limited."
In May, the bank forecast growth of 1.9 percent for this year and 1.7 percent for next year.
It now kept its 2018 growth forecast at 1.8%.
The pound weakened against the dollar and euro following the news.
Against the dollar, the pound weakened 0.5 per cent to $1.31. Against the euro, it weakened 0.4 per cent to €1.11.
The decision to keep interest rates unchanged was made after weaker-than-expected growth figures dampened increased expectations for rate hikes. GDP grew 0.3 percent in the second quarter and 0.2 percent in the first quarter.
The bank expects growth to remain at 0.3 percent in the third quarter but to pick up slightly at the end of the year.
Its latest inflation review gave little hope to households suffering from accelerating inflation and meagre pay rises. The Bank says the situation will get even worse before it gets better.
The bank added that monetary policy "cannot prevent" incomes from falling over the next few years. However, it expects that wage growth will recover "significantly" at the end of the three-year forecast period.
The economy will also be bolstered by strong growth in demand for British goods as a result of the weak pound. It will reverse some of the impact of falling private consumption.
The decision was taken a year after interest rates were cut to 0.25 per cent following a shock EU referendum result that plunged the pound.
The bank reckons that the overall impact of the decision is not likely to start to show up in prices and the economy until four years from now.
Ahead of the central bank's latest decision, calls for rate hikes had become increasingly loud as inflation ratcheted up pressure on households. Three policymakers called for a 0.5 percent rate hike in July.
Inflation eased to 2.6 per cent last month from 2.9 per cent in June. However, the Bank said it was expected and inflation will tighten again in the coming months.
The bank said its 2 per cent overshoot of the target level was "entirely due" to the weak pound.
