NHS to prescribe 10,000 controversial HIV drugs
From September, patients can be prescribed a "turnaround" anti-HIV drug. A dispute over the drug's funding in England's public health system (NHS) was concluded in the Supreme Court.
The NHS announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) will be prescribed to around 10,000 people during the first three-year trial. A drug taken before intercourse has been found to reduce the risk of transmission by around 86 per cent in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld last year's judgment by the High Court. It says the NHS will be able to pay for the PrEP drug, despite arguing that it should be funded by local authorities.
Simon Stevens, head of the NHS in England, called the decision announced on Thursday a "significant new intervention," and the national AIDS charity described it as a "decisively important moment."
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to start accepting enrolments for the trial, which will expand to other clinics in October. The trial will reach its full extent in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV medicine taken before intercourse that reduces the risk of transmission.
Experiments have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in high-risk groups.
The drug taken before intercourse means that there are enough drugs in the body during intercourse to prevent HIV infection.
The drug can be taken daily or two hours before sex.
The treatment target group includes gay men, bisexual men and transgender people, as well as people with an HIV-positive partner who do not receive effective treatment.
Clinics will select eligible applicants from men, women and transgender people, as well as those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to be receiving antiretroviral therapy for their disease.
People living in England and registered with a GP can also apply for a trial at their local sexual health clinic.
The programme will cost £10m, and the NHS in England this week signed a procurement contract for the drugs after an international tender.
The trial is designed to assess the potential of the PrEP drug by gathering extensive clinical evidence on its targeting, taking and treatment implementation.
"This significant new intervention should complement and enhance the diverse and increasingly effective means already in place to prevent HIV," said Stevens.
"It's yet another remarkable achievement in a battle that has been going on for more than 30 years to tackle one of humanity's greatest health challenges."
"This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV," says Deborah Gold, executive director of the National AIDS Organization.
"If PrEP is correctly targeted at those who need it and those at risk, it could have an epochal impact on England's HIV epidemic.
From September, those at risk will receive a drug, through an NHS-funded trial, that they can decide on independently without the need to negotiate with a partner. It will have an empowering effect that will improve the lives of very many people.
That was welcome news.”
"The priority now is to ensure that the trial is launched quickly across the country and no one at risk is excluded," said Ian Green, director of the Terrence Higgins Foundation.
"The PrEP drug being used in the trial has been acquired, and we will soon be able to protect ten thousand people at risk from HIV infection."
"The start of the PrEP trial is a welcome event that was prolonged in vain by several months due to government slowing down," says Sharon Hodgson, the shadow cabinet secretary for health.
"We have evidence that the drug can have an epochal impact on the work we do to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this threatening disease.
The trial will help us to better understand the real benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the trial is launched as soon as possible across the country, so that we can protect those exposed to HIV and get one step closer to halting the spread of HIV in society."
Quality of life: the mezzanine floor and smart interior design solutions have made the small Earl's Court apartment a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker enthusiastic about property renovations, moved from a residential area of Knightsbridge to a smaller flat in Earl's Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the first floor of a Queen Anna-style house. The success of the renovation is evidenced by the fact that Joanne has not yet packed up her things and moved in.
"Before this, my ex and I lived in a considerably larger flat in Knightsbridge," says Joanne.
"I'm looking for something similar in my price range.
I went to an apartment display here and found that the rooms were as high as they were in my apartment at the time.
I loved it and made an offer the same day.”
Since then, the roughly 90-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete makeover.
It was a two-room apartment where the bedroom could only be accessed from the kitchen. Joanne wanted more storage space as well as a mezzanine floor to make the most of the room height.
"I wanted space, big windows and lots of light.
Those were my demands," he says.
He hired Erfan Azad from Duck & Shed, a design agency in Notting Hill. Erfan was tasked with making the most of the space in the nearly four-metre-high rooms and creating an apartment that would not just be a subject for renovation and sale but a home.
The room height was not quite enough for two overlapping spaces, so the challenge was to build a mezzanine floor where you could stand.
The solution required creative thinking on Erfan's part.
"Steel structures are quite complex.
The spaces had to be arranged on top of each other so that there was no need to cower in them.
The structures had to be modified so that the height is just right both on top of them and underneath."
Erfan was able to place two full-height rooms on top of each other in the space with fascinating details.
On the mezzanine floor, a Retrouvius copper-crusted window opens to a sleek lounge.
Mirror-gold furniture, silver effects and Serge Mouille's vintage lamps create a signature style.
The use of mirrors brings theatricality, a sense of space and light.
Mirrors at either end of the short corridor make the corridor seem longer than the real thing.
A mirror in the middle of the kitchen is like a window overlooking another room.
The mirrored furniture at the entrance has storage for Joanne's cutlery and glassware.
Adding to the elegance is the fact that you can hide the kitchen when you're not using it.
Folding-door kitchens are not a new solution,
but what's unique about Joanne's kitchen is that the door is lifted up in the same way as a garage door.
"It took a little planning," Erfan tells me of the steel-reinforced veneer-surfaced MDF door.
"It's balanced, meaning it slides very easily into place when lifted."
With sensible use of space and planning for storage, Joanne got 16 extra square metres, a second bedroom and an even better layout.
"When selling a home, it's the acreage that counts – or the valuation of the property," says Erfan.
"Basically, an estate agent walks into an apartment and calculates the price based on surface area."
In Joanne's apartment, the surface area was increased by using high-quality materials that bring luxury to the space.
"The resident is in contact with the materials in the apartment, and the emotional bond to the apartment is partly created based on them," Erfan says.
"No one's getting attached to the electrical wires that go through the walls.
They're important too, but not in the same way."
Joanne's flat is an example of how good design and extra square metres can make a basic flat exceptionally fine.
It may also mean that you no longer want to move out of the apartment.
