"His actions killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
"He ended Conrad's life to improve his own.
He has not accepted responsibility for the act," the prosecutor continued.
"He has shown no remorse."
Carter's attorney said the case stemmed from "shocking circumstances that Carter deeply regrets."
But Judge Lawrence Moniz ruled that neither Carter's "age or level of maturity, nor even mental health problems, had a significant impact on what he did."
The prosecutor read a statement from Conrad's mother, Lynn Roy, who told him that "not a day goes by that I don't mourn the death of my beloved son.
I want her to be able to be proud of me and how I am coping with all of this. I will try my best to comfort her sisters in this pain we will always carry."
Conrad's sister Camdyn Roy told the court she was "persecuted" by the thought of never seeing her brother's wedding and not being an aunt to his children.
