Murder of Journalist Embodies Growing Threat in Mexico
The editorial board of the once-weekly Riodoce newspaper usually meets Wednesday to discuss how the paper handles the latest cases involving organized crime, corrupt authorities and the interminable drug war in Sinaloa state.
Today, however, safety is being discussed because of the recent tragedy.
Journalists have been told to change their daily routines.
Two seasoned reporters discuss which is safer: leaving the children at home or taking them with them to a delivery that was hit by a grenade attack in 2009.
Security experts have written three words on the blackboard at the front of the room: opponents, neutrals, allies.
They ask reporters for names for each group. No evidence is required, observations and sensations are sufficient.
Names of drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen and journalists suspected of being on the payroll of the government or drug cartels are written on the board. They are criminals who make news coverage of the chaos in Mexico life-threatening.
Violence is incessant, increasingly targeting journalists. According to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 journalists have been murdered since President Enrique Peña Nieto took office in December 2012. There are 589 journalists under federal protection who have been attacked and threatened. At least seven journalists have been murdered in seven states this year.
Among the latest victims is Javier Valdez Cardenas, founder, journalist and inspiration for Riodoce.
"The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist," Valdez wrote in one of his many books on drug violence.
He is deeply missed, though he is omnipresent. The facade of the building in Riodoce is covered by a huge picture showing Valdez with a middle finger. The image reads: "Justice." Journalists Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, in their 30s, are dressed in T-shirts adorned with Valdez's smiling face. Valdez wears glasses and a trademark panama hat.
The meeting will take place less than two months after Valdez's death. Reporters will discuss their shared trauma, nightmares, insomnia and fears that have escalated into paranoia.
A federal prosecutor's office was set up in 2010 specifically to handle journalists' cases, but only two charges have been filed so far, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
Murderers of journalists are rarely tried, as are thousands of murders linked to drug trafficking and organised crime each year.
Riodoce journalists plan to continue writing about the violence in Sinaloa, even though they are heartbroken and the situation is even more dangerous.
Ibarra said the security meeting is of limited use because the killers are not known and there is no hope for justice.
"This meeting is, frankly, a waste of time," he says.
"We can't trust anyone as long as we don't know the cause of the incident."
Valdez had left Riodocé in Culiacan, the state capital, on the morning of 15 May 2017.
He had driven only a couple of blocks in his red Toyota when two men stopped him and forced him out of his car and fired twelve shots. The number is presumably related to the name of the magazine: Riodoce means twelfth river.
The shooter drove off in Valdez's car and crashed it some distance away.
Valdez was 50.
He is survived by a wife and two adult children.
Rumours are moving fast and running freely in Culiacan.
Valdez's death, however, is being muzzled.
Sinaloa has been one of Mexico's bloodiest battlegrounds since Guzman was arrested last year and deported to the U.S. in January. Rival factions want to fill the void.
On the streets of Sinaloa, someone or several people are shot dead every day, and the cemetery houses the ornate two-story burial buildings of drug barons, larger than the homes of many.
In a coastal state, it is "peaceful" when only one cartel controls ports and drug trafficking routes to the United States.
While Valdez was well aware of the dangers of his job, Riodoce's founder and director, 60-year-old Ismail Bojorquez, feels guilty for not being able to protect his friend.
He believes two mistakes led to Valdez's murder.
In February, Riodoce published an interview with Damaso Lopez, the leader of a rival faction waging war against Guzman's sons.
The story may have angered Guzman's sons: Customers suspected of being gang members bought every issue of the paper as soon as the paper hit the outlets.
Another mistake was not forcing Valdez to leave the country after another paper with the same story came under attack.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder is seen as a turning point in violence against journalists.
He had survived so many that his friends and colleagues could no longer fear for him.
He had had a long career at Noroeste when, in 2003, he and five colleagues decided to set up Riodoce. The paper's shares were selling for $50 at the time.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without dealing with the drug problem," Bojorquez tells me.
In time, the magazine became known for its bold and honest stories, and its sales and advertising revenue grew.
Journalists appreciated the opportunity to publish hard-core investigative journalism without fear of censorship, and readers were fascinated by stories in the paper that no one else dared publish.
Eight years after its founding, Riodoce won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Award for its coverage in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez received the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee to Protect Journalists for his courage in relentlessly following the story of Mexico's drug trade.
He openly admitted he was afraid.
"I want to be able to move on with my life," he said as he received an award from the Committee to Protect Journalists.
Drug trafficking is a "lifestyle" in Sinaloa, Valdez said in an interview with Rompeviento TV last October.
“A journalist must accept a task that falls to him – or act stupid.
I don’t want anyone to have to ask me where I was when death was being sown here – why didn’t I tell you what was going on?”
The staff at Riodoce miss Valdez – a joker who cursed like a dock worker. They miss a friend who always gave them a hug and advice. They miss a teacher who knew how to cope.
They relied on his routine.
He always wore a panama hat.
He went to the El Guayabo bar across the street and always sat at the same table.
Now they ask if the routine was his downfall.
The death of a colleague has also led them to consider how best to do their jobs and stay alive.
"Criminals won't like it if we cover their women and children and their clean businesses, their secret drug trafficking runways in our cases.
They were excluded from the cases," says Bojorquez.
It meant, at best, strong self-censorship and self-preservation,
Trust your own instincts.
If you feel like everything is not right, you have to stay away.
The problem, according to Riodoce editor Andres Villarreal, is that "the impression can fail, and that's what happened in Javier's case."
The old rules no longer apply in Sinaloa, nor do they apply in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states with dangerous networks: attractive smuggling routes, weak agencies and corrupt authorities.
The operating environment is constantly changing.
Mobile phones were not allowed to be brought into the room where Riodoce's security training was held. A few days earlier, reports had emerged that only spyware sold to governments had tracked activists and journalists in Mexico.
Outside the building, two police officers had taken shelter in the shade of a tree from the 40-degree heat.
They had been ordered by the state government to guard Riodoce's premises, which are housed in a four-storey building in the middle-class Culiacan region.
Some of the reporters half-jokingly guessed whether it was these two police officers who were among the 50 percent who the state governor didn't think were trustworthy.
It had been months since journalists had visited the mountainous countryside dominated by drug gangs.
For this week's issue, Riodoce's editorial team envisaged three main stories.
The brother of boxing great Julio Cesar Chavez had been killed in Sinaloa.
The newspaper also planned to reveal that the government's spending was concentrated in the governor's hometown.
In addition, at one of Culiacan's most expensive restaurants, just blocks from the prosecutor's office, a group of people were kidnapped.
There was no official word on who had been kidnapped and how, so tread carefully: everyone in the city knew that the restaurant was popular with both drug traffickers and authorities.
A journalist discovered from public records that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI). The PRI has dominated Mexican politics at all levels for nearly a century.
Its governors have recently been accused of corruption in much-publicised cases.
Villarreal asked a reporter to write about previous incidents at the same location. In one of them, "El Chapo" Guzman's son managed to escape and avoid an army raid.
A few months earlier, readers would have known they were getting reliable information about the kidnapping from Valdez's column.
"In the past, we would have already known what had happened," says Villarreal, 46, who has been nicknamed "El Flaco," Thinner, because of his slim physique.
"Now all communications with our sources of information are down."
Valdez's study has been turned into a warehouse to store signs and stickers against the persecution of journalists. The paper's employees have been given a new, unexpected task: They have become activists advocating press freedom.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took a few signs with her as she headed to a rally outside the local prosecutor's office the next morning, prompted by yet another murder of a journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in the western state of Michoacan three days after Valdez's murder.
After the disappearance, a burned body was found, which, based on DNA tests conducted by authorities, is Adame.
Journalists have begun to protest louder across the country. In demonstrations, "SOS Press" texts appear on sidewalks and buildings.
Today, leader Bojorquez is in Washington, where he is trying to win international support for an investigation into the Valdez case.
The day after Valdez's murder, Ramirez met with Sinaloa's governor and accused authorities of spying on and killing journalists for telling the truth.
He has since asked to be removed from cases dealing with the government out of concern that he is unable to be objective in his anger.
Valdez had repeatedly noted that journalists in Mexico were surrounded by organized crime, crime-permitting authorities and an indifferent society.
In his last book, Narcojournalism, Valdez writes that drug gangs kill journalists, but they are also killed at the behest of politicians and security forces in agreement with organized crime.
Articulo 19, a watchdog group, said more than half of the attacks on journalists last year were the work of police and authorities.
"In Mexico, people are silenced by killing," Ramirez says.
The murders have a paralyzing effect.
No one will forget the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias in the northern border state of Tamaulipas six years ago.
At his body was a note signed by the Zetas cartel: "I am here for my writings."
Next to his severed head was a computer keyboard and headphones.
Some of the newspapers have decided to shut down, such as El Norte newspaper in the northern border state of Chihuahua after the March murder of correspondent Miroslava Breach.
Some continue to operate, like Nuevo Laredo's El Manana, even though its leader was assassinated in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juarez posted a message on its front page to drug cartels: "What do you want from us?"
Some journalists have fled their states or the country as a whole.
It's a difficult decision.
It's hard to find work in exile, and you have to be on your guard all the time.
Sometimes criminals will seek out a journalist, as was apparently the case with photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was murdered with four women in a Mexico City apartment in 2015 three months after fleeing Veracruz.
For those who continue to work, every day is filled with dangerous decisions.
Ibarra – who was once going to be a poet – admits that writing about drug dealing scares me.
"I became a journalist because Mexico is on its way to hell," he tells me.
Not long ago, Riodoce reporters sat in front of a delivery on Friday at midnight on the sidewalk with a beer as the latest issue of the magazine was completed. Suddenly, their phones began vibrating to signal the message.
A shootout between rival gangs and security forces in the beach resort of Mazatlan had left 19 people dead.
The war escalated, as promised in cartel messages found in the area.
Reporters posted the news on Riodoce's Web site from the sidewalk with their smartphones.
The front page had to be redone the next day.
Sirens wailed nearby – another shooting scene.
Bojorquez glanced at the police officers guarding the delivery:
If they were scared, they covered it up very well.
Riodoce's editorial team continued the tradition of the magazine's murdered founder under this massive portrait of a man showing the middle finger to all of Sinaloa.
Bojorquez says he can't even consider shutting down operations. "How could I shut down a magazine when our intern asked to go out on the street and still do a story the same day Javier had been murdered?"
