Dinosaur Protects Its Enemies by Disguising Itself
At first it looks like a scary statue.
Now scientists have revealed the first research results of a rhino-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner that was so well preserved that experts are calling it the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.
It had been so well preserved that scientists were even able to define that its scaly skin was reddish-brown and had had a "problematic past."
According to the journal Current Biology, it is the best-preserved armoured dinosaur of all time and among the best of its kind in the world.
The newly discovered fossil is a nodosaurus that lived in the mid-Cretaceous period 110 to 112 million years ago.
Scientists consider this amazingly well-preserved fossil to be a truly remarkable find.
According to National Geographic magazine, the armored vegetarian is the best-preserved fossil of its kind ever.
It was found in the Suncor Millenium mine in Northern Alberta, Canada on 21 March 2011, by a miner named Shawn Funk.
He hit something that didn't seem to be a natural part of the surrounding rock, and decided to investigate his discovery further.
The fossil found in the rock was sent to the Royal Paleontological Museum in Tyrrell.
There, the beast was excavated for six years from a 1,100-pound boulder.
The results of the hard work are now visible.
"If you squint your eyes, you can almost believe it was asleep," says science writer Caleb Brown, who works as a researcher at the Tyrrell Royal Museum.
"It will go down in the history of science as the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs, one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaurs.
Studies of the skin revealed that meat-eating dinosaurs likely posed a significant threat to this vegetarian, even though it had armor and resembled a walking tank.
Its red-and-white armor camouflaged it from predators, and it was also protected by a darker and lighter coloration on the top, which is still found in many animals.
Experts say this allowed it to better mix with its surroundings and avoid its enemies, the larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old nodosaurus made headlines in May, and is now on display at the Royal Paleontological Museum in Tyrrell.
Scientists have named it the Borealope markmitchelli, after museum technician Mark Mitchell. Mitchell was part of a team that took more than 7,000 hours to excavate the dinosaur.
Nodosaurus has been so amazingly preserved that Mitchell and an international team of scientists have been able to determine the patterns and shape of its body scales and armor.
They found that it was still protected by the colouring common in the animal world, where the body is darker on top and lighter underneath.
Still, the sighting was a surprise because the Borealope is significantly larger than today's animals, which have a similar coloration.
It suggests that meat-eating dinosaurs preyed on it to such an extent that evolution favoured hiding as a means of survival over fighting.
Among modern animals, for example, deer, zebras and armadillos have a similar coloration. They are significantly smaller and therefore easier prey, suggesting that the nodosaur was also seriously threatened.
"The predation of a large, heavily armoured dinosaur tells you how dangerous Cretaceous dinosaurs were," says Brown.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in the scales of Nodosaurus reveals that its skin was reddish brown.
Scientists continue to study the nodosaur in order to draw conclusions about its life, including examining the contents of its gut to find out what it ate at its last meal.
Scientists believe that when it died it fell into a river and drifted out to sea, where it sank on its back to the seabed.
Alberta was as warm then as it is today in Florida, and rivers and seas likely extended much further than they do today.
"This nodosaurus is really remarkable because its scaly skin has been preserved and it has also been preserved in three dimensions in its original form," notes Brown.
"That's why it looks almost the same as it did in the early Cretaceous
It doesn't take much imagination to figure it out: if you squint a little at the eyes, you can almost believe it was asleep."
The Cretaceous was the age of theropods, huge bipedal, flesh-eating dinosaurs.
Although their king, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years before the Borealopeltah, its mighty predecessors may have preyed on this armoured dinosaur.
Tyrannosaurus rex's predecessors, for example, included Acrocanthosaurus, a six-ton monster about 11.5 meters long.
The latest findings from the Nodosaurus researchers have been published in the journal Current Biology. They believe the Borealope was washed out to sea after his death and mummified in mud.
It was found in the Suncor Millenium mine in Northern Alberta, Canada on 21 March 2011, by a miner named Shawn Funk.
The museum says it is the world's best preserved armoured dinosaur with skins and armour from snout to hip.
The nodosaurs averaged five meters long and weighed up to 1,300 pounds.
Two six-foot spikes rose from their pallets.
Scientists believe this armored vegetarian passed through what is now Western Canada until a flooded river carried it offshore.
Its armor is preserved in minute detail in an undersea tomb.
Its fossilized remains have been preserved so well that its skin remains in the pitted plates of armor along its skull.
As Michael Greshko wrote in National Geographic, such preservation is "as rare as winning the lottery.
The closer you look at it, the more astounding it feels.
The bumpy plates of its skull armour still contain fossilised leather.
Its right front foot is on its side, five toes up.
I can count the scales on its sole, too.'
How did one activist learn to answer the question: Who do the streets belong to?
Brittany Ferrell was deeply shocked on August 9, 2014.
He had arrived in New York a day earlier from his home in St. Louis and was sitting on the bed of his airbnb apartment, scrolling through Facebook on his phone.
That's when he noticed a note from his high school friend:
"Police just killed an 18-year-old youth. His body is still in the street."
Confused, she noted that no one else had posted the same information on her feed. That's why she shut down Facebook and opened Twitter.
Her timeline featured numerous retweets from user @TheePharoah.
The username belongs to a St. Louis-based rapper who tweeted in real time about the death of Michael Brown. Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old Black man, had been shot by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
The user in question had also posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body in the street, where it was left for four hours.
"This is unbelievable," Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to him and his community.
He put his phone away. When he returned to Twitter later that night, there were reports of people gathering on Canfield Drive.
Users posted photos of police cordons and screaming people, as well as a man claiming to be Brown's father, with a sign carrying the words: "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
Ferrell followed real-time video footage showing police standing in front of protesters with a barking dog.
He says he also saw a video of another officer cocking his rifle and shouting, "I'm going to kill all you... animals."
"This is not normal," Ferrell remembers stating.
"It was not the kind of murder we are already used to and could be said to be typical.
That's when I felt chills.
I was angry and crying.”
He booked a return flight home for the next day.
The plane landed at 11 o'clock in the evening. Ferrell stopped by his father's house to pick up his six-year-old daughter and decided they would go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson within the next nearly three years has been made into a documentary, "Whose Streets?". It premiered in cinemas on 11 August 2017.
The film is a story of survival and protest, love and loss, and strength and resilience from the perspective of the local people who took to the streets to demand answers.
As Ferrell drove toward Ferguson with her daughter, who was dressed in a floral dress and matching crown, they had a renewed conversation about "what it's like to live as a Black person and under what conditions." They had spoken about it countless times before that morning.
"Remember when I told you how Black people have had to fight for the things they believe in?" Ferrell remembers saying to his daughter.
"We are going to Ferguson because a police officer killed an 18-year-old boy and that is not right."
"I couldn't help but take my daughter with me," Ferrell later told me.
"Today's events are... the culmination of events of the past.
My daughter has a right to know that and to grow into it.
She needs to be equipped for activism and organizing, but she also needs to know the different layers and circumstances of the experience of living as a Black person. And she needs to know what we need to do to be liberated, to liberate ourselves.
While I've been fortunate enough to be able to protect her from blatant racism, she's still just like every other Black girl.
I feel like I would hurt him if I protected him from reality.'
Their first stop in Ferguson was South Florissant Road, which is opposite the police station. It became a campground for activists as they waited for information about the handling of the case and eventually learned that no charges would be filed against the officer.
From there, Ferrell and her daughter went to help a local entrepreneur who made lunch packages.
They packed lunches in bags and handed them out to protesters.
Ferrell gradually began to take a new approach to activism.
"My activism completely changed after Aug. 9," she tells me. While studying at the University of Missouri in St. Louis, Ferrell was president of an organization of minority nursing students. At the time, she focused on food justice and health disparities in Black communities.
“I had no experience in organizing.
Somehow it just happened.”
Weeks later, Ferrell met at an evening rally with Sabaah Folayan, the documentary's assistant director.
Folayan said he and cinematographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar "simply wanted to tell" what was happening.
A suspicion crept into Ferrell's mind. He asked: "Do you really want to tell me what's happening, or do you want a story you can exploit?"
At the root of the suspicion were the countless times people, usually white, had turned up in the local community wanting only to profit from its hardships and resilience.
"We had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson didn't have a common voice," Folayan told me in a recent interview. "We wanted to do things differently."
Folayan had already reached out to assistant director Damon Davis, who is known for his activism with death row inmates.
Davis' involvement prompted Ferrell to join the effort, along with six other locals. A film crew followed events in the years following Brown's shooting.
"This is not a documentary where someone speaks to us or speaks for us, we speak," Davis says.
"The most important thing for me was how the local people are portrayed in the film because I'm portrayed in the same way."
According to Folayan, the intention was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences because of the desire to show that the popular movement "is not about a charismatic leader but about the community." Ferrell, however, proved to be the most open of those described.
