Fitting resemblance: artist creates portraits from Chelsea Manning's DNA
The Fridman Gallery in New York has hung faces in the middle of the exhibition space – white, black and brown faces, between which, on closer inspection, you can see a resemblance.
These 30 works are portraits made by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg, based on DNA samples taken from Chelsea Manning's cheek and hair.
Manning sent the samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where he was serving his 35-year sentence. Manning was convicted of leaking classified diplomatic cables to WikiLeaks.
Dewey-Hagborg's A Becoming Resemblance exhibition opened on 2 August 2017.
Underpinning it is two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg and Manning. Dewey-Hagborg combines technology, information technology and art in her work. Manning is a trans woman and pioneering dissident whose prison sentence was commuted by Barack Obama on the third last day of her tenure.
Dewey-Hagborg analyzed Manning's DNA algorithmically and created 30 portraits based on his genetic data. They are a sharp, if somewhat theoretical, statement of the malleability, ambiguity and cause-and-effect relationships behind the interpretations, as well as identity.
Chelsea Manning, born Bradley Edward, has openly said she has identified with women since puberty. She was found guilty in 2013 of 20 offences, including a breach of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
There was only one image of Manning, who was sentenced to prison: a grainy, black-and-white selfie of an ailing Manning sitting in the driver's seat in the car. He's wearing the platinum-blond wig that became his signature.
Dewey-Hagborg was behind the hugely successful Stranger Visions project in 2015, which he implemented in 2012.
In it, he created portraits based on forensic data. He obtained DNA data from items such as cigarette butts and chewing gum and created images of what the people in question might have looked like.
Then the artist received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning and needed a picture for their case," Dewey-Hagborg told a news conference for the new show.
Unable to visit Manning and unable to be photographed in prison, the paper contacted Chelsea and asked if she would be interested in making a DNA portrait of Manning.
The artist and his imprisoned muse suddenly became pen pals, writing to each other for a couple of years.
They even made a Suppressed Images comic book together, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo. It described a future where the president would have commuted Chelsea's sentence and she would get to see the exhibition.
In reality, Obama reduced Manning's sentence just a few days after the comic book was published. It was a lucky coincidence after seven rough years in a Kansas military prison.
It's also impressive that the exhibit is opening right now as Donald Trump is waging his own war against leakers and transgender soldiers and coming up with ever-new ways on Twitter to reinforce the powerful divides he was supposed to actually mitigate.
Dewey-Hagborg believes that "everything has a purpose."
On the gallery wall is an artist's statement and underneath is Manning's large autograph, with the last name i's dotted on the heart. In the statement, the artist calls for an end to the "automatic division on which gender, race, sexuality and culture have been based."
On the opposite wall is Manning's DNA sequence: a long line of letters C, G and A written in pencil.
With this combination of 200 letters – or nucleotides, as the artist uses a scientific definition – Dewey-Hagborg wants to illustrate how similar we all are, at least in terms of our biology.
"I hope my exhibition will help people understand that we are equal in our genetic heritage and that genetic information is very personal and open to interpretation," says Dewey-Hagborg. The exhibition also features her Spurious Memories video work from 2007.
"DNA tells countless stories. There are 30 of them on display here."
The last work in the exhibition is in its own room: a page from a comic book by Manning and Dewey-Hagborg.
In it, Manning's character rises from prison like King Kong, holding a megaphone.
"If they can silence you, they've won," the photo reads.
"Never be silent."
"The text is from a letter I received from Manning," the Philadelphia-based artist says.
"It's so impressive, I still get chills."
Contrary to what was described in the comic book, Manning has yet to see the exhibit. When Manning shows up, he is greeted by a face based on his own genetic information like a crowd of protesters in the middle of the exhibit space.
It's intentional, as is everything else in this exhibition: Manning's DNA sequence, for example, is written in pencil at a height equal to his height (157.5 cm).
"The faces used to be on the wall, but I wanted to bring a sense of a crowd to them," says Dewey-Hagborg.
"I wanted to describe the mass movement Chelsea generated, which was also behind her release."
