It also recently signed a deal with Uber.
Similar to Glint, Convercent allows companies to conduct customized surveys, collect responses confidentially in real time and map problem areas.
In addition, employees can report inappropriate behavior anonymously by text message.
And if there is reason to suspect a manager of improprieties, complaints go directly to the company's board of directors.
"Public opinion has sidelined the authorities," says Patrick Quinlan, Convercent's founder and chief executive.
He reminds that if a company mistreats its employees or acts unethically, the consequences can be costly, even if the authorities do not intervene. Consumers can start boycotting a company, and it can also lose employees and be sued.
