The Birth of a Comic Book: The Story of a Castle
The tiny Scotney Castle in County Kent is now known for Squeeze's music video as well as Margaret Thatcher's hideout from the 1970s and 1980s.
But it has 700 years of turbulent history behind it. Now, this castle, in a charming location in the Bewl River Valley, is the subject of a comic book by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-haired writer with a penchant for old documents.
"I think it's great to be able to study a text written by someone who died over 300 years ago," Rhodes says longingly.
"I feel a personal connection as I hold the letter in my hand."
Rhodes's book, A Castle in England, tells the stories of families who lived in Scotney from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era. Each story has been illustrated by a different artist, a promising British cartoonist: Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer or Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes's first book based on archives. In 2014, he published Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories, inspired by documents from Britain's National Library. The project was emotional.
"I was moved to tears when I noticed a thumbprint on the letter. The letter had been written by a double agent who worked for Jacobites in the 18th century," says Rhodes.
"It was his fingerprints!
And the letters smell like smoke, because at that time fire was used as lighting.
Three centuries later, the scent makes the reader feel that he or she is on the spot himself or herself.
I love the archives!"
The author, attracted to old documents, was allowed to live in the castle for almost four months with the support of the National Trust and the National Arts Council of England, which seemed too good to be true. He admits he couldn't wait to stay in the castle a little longer than would have been hoped.
He spent days researching the Victorian "new" castle, archives, treasures and rarities such as hyena heads hung on walls and bottles in a moat for centuries.
He toured the ruins and estates of the old castle and chatted with rangers, gardeners and sometimes artists illustrating the book.
In the evenings, he "took whiskey and started writing."
Scotney's closer history is fairly unknown, as the castle was not passed entirely to the National Trust until the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived about a dozen years later, the foundation's staff was just beginning to go through the archive. Rhodes describes that the archives had been kept for hundreds of years using the same method: taking any excess to the attic.
The archives contained diaries, letters from the days of the English Empire and maps of who owned what. "You'd imagine land disputes are boring," Rhodes says. "Here, though, families even fought over one birch.
I thought we should let it be.”
Some of the stories in the book progress from the castle to English history, such as The Labourer. It's about a man who joins shortly after the castle's completion in England's Peasants' Revolt in 1381.
"The Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex book mentions that there was a riot at the castle in 1380," says Rhodes.
"The English peasant rebellion began in the same area, and it occurred to me that rebellion can start with a riot.
Maybe these events are connected?”
