Red meat, dairy and chocolate may alleviate irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like digestive system nightmares.
However, a recent study claims the opposite: a diet high in meat protein and dairy products may ease irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritable bowel syndrome is an incurable condition that affects around 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 people in the UK. It causes stomach cramps, bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhoea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Irritable bowel syndrome sufferers are generally advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, researchers at Washington University found that the essential amino acid tryptophan in the protein helps the body develop immune cells that strengthen gut tolerance.
According to Marco Colonna, the head of the study, immune cells guard the marsh and ensure that harmful microbes hiding in food do not enter the body.
Inflammatory cells are balanced by cells that strengthen tolerance. They protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to inflammation, the result can be irritable bowel syndrome.
Tests found that immune cells that strengthen tolerance are found in mice with a specific bacteria in their guts.
The bacterium in question needs tryptophan for immune cells to start showing up. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
"We found a link between Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of cells that promote resilience. Lactobacillus reuteri is part of the normal gut microbiome," explains Professor Colonna.
"The more tryptophan in the diet of mice, the more they had such immune cells."
If the same works in humans, the combination of Lactobacillus reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan can strengthen gut tolerance and reduce inflammatory sensitivity.
Studying immune cells that strengthen resilience, postdoctoral researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that while one group of mice had such cells, they were not present in mice of the same mouse species that were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the gut microbiomes of mice, or the normal community of bacteria, fungi and viruses in the gastrointestinal tract.
When the gut DNA of the mice was examined, six species of bacteria were detected in those mice that had immune cells but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria were given to mice that grew in a sterile environment and had no gut microbiome and did not develop immune cells, they began to show up with immune cells.
The researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system. They grew Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in liquid and transferred small amounts of fluid – without the bacteria – to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells evolved into cells that strengthen resilience.
When the active ingredient was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of the metabolism of tryptophan, known as indole-3 lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's food, the number of cells that could strengthen tolerance rose by about 50 percent. When the number of tryptophan was halved, the number of cells dropped by half from earlier.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, humans have the same tolerance-boosting cells as mice, and most of us have Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our digestive tract.
It is not yet known whether the by-products of tryptophan, Lactobacillus reuteri, cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as they do in mice. However, genetic defects associated with tryptophan have been observed in people with irritable bowel syndrome.
"We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate inflammation on the inner surfaces of the intestines," says Cervantes-Barragan.
"High levels of tryptophan combined with Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria may contribute to their proliferation".
