White House exhibit cost thousands of dollars to taxpayers
The White House's decision last month to fly a Navy helicopter to the White House's South Lawn for an event featuring American production came at a cost to taxpayers of $24,000. The information appears in military documents obtained by TIME.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter is referred to as Marine One when the president is aboard. It was the attraction at an event at the White House on July 17, 2017, to showcase American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and a number of White House officials took a look at the products from all 50 states.
In addition to the Connecticut-made helicopter, exhibits included a sailboat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
The White House military office had requested the helicopter on a mission-specific order only about 36 hours before it landed in the southern grass field for the "extraordinary" event. This is clear from documents from the Navy's HMX-1 helicopter fleet.
"I just wanted to make sure you were aware of the issue because this is an extraordinary event that is getting a lot of coverage," the commander of the HMX-1 unit wrote in an e-mail message to his supervisor, who is an assistant commandant in the Navy's Joint Chiefs of Staff, the day before the incident.
The message said the helicopter would arrive at the southern grass field around 7 a.m. on July 17 and the event would begin at 3 in the afternoon. The helicopter would only leave the scene after the grass field was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m. in the evening.
The note also mentioned that if the helicopter's departure from the White House was delayed, a second crew would be needed because of restrictions on service hours.
The original crew was in the helicopter for the duration of the incident, and security personnel from the unit were by the helicopter when it was on the ground.
It is not clear from the documents obtained by TIME whether another crew was ultimately needed.
The U.S. Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
According to the documents, HMX-1 inquired whether the event violates the law.
"One of our questions was whether there was a violation of the Hatch Act here. We were told there would be no violation," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you can participate," the assistant commandant replied.
Made in America was an official White House event, so it was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the president spoke in favor of health care reform, which was under consideration in the Senate at the time, as well as looser state regulation.
The use of Marine One helicopter and Air Force One for political purposes is not a new phenomenon.
Presidents must wear them on their travels,
but their use only for photographs is unusual.
Trump's actions drew attention in February when Air Force One rolled into the backdrop of a presidential campaign event in Melbourne, Florida. Trump has strongly criticized his predecessor's use of the presidential aircraft on Twitter.
"The White House is very pleased with Made in America, which showcased products made from American materials by American workers from all 50 states," stated White House Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
Crews from the HMX-1 unit regularly conduct training flights in the Washington area and practice on the southern grass field to bring the president to the White House with centimetre accuracy.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings for the White House.
One official said the flights to Made in America were part of the crew's monthly training quota.
The unit's helicopters that day also flew 11 hours in "non-presidential support missions."
The White House said the event did not incur any other costs for taxpayers.
A spokeswoman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in organizing the helicopter demonstration on the South Lawn of the White House.
HMX-1 has no accounting for flights related to presidential duties, and it is difficult to accurately estimate the event's expenses.
According to the Department of Defense's 2017 hourly allowances, the replacement level for a VH-3D helicopter is $24,380 per flight hour.
According to HMX-1 unit documents, flights from the Quantico base in Virginia state to and from the White House took a total of one hour.
The White House says the cost of operating the helicopter will be markedly lower.
"Calculating the cost to taxpayers according to the level of compensation is misleading," Walters says.
"The estimated compensation level includes staffing, maintenance and many other so-called embedded costs that are factored into the annual allocation."
According to a 2015 study by research firm RAND, compensation levels do not include staff costs but do take into account fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
Around the time of the event, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer excused the use of a helicopter at the event.
"The idea is to showcase American production," Spicer said.
"I know Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud to be involved in ensuring national security and employing probably hundreds or thousands of people.
And I think like most Americans, we're proud of the helicopter and other defense equipment that a lot of Americans have worked hard for.
It's perfectly appropriate to bring that up.'
It's not certain if Trump visited the helicopter during the event, but at least he sat down in the driver's seat of the fire truck.
