NYT: Trump's glowering phone calls were made up - White House spokesman: "I wouldn't say it was a lie"
The White House admits that two phone calls mentioned by US President Donald Trump never took place, according to the New York Times.
Trump's incensed phone calls with both Mexico's president and the leader of the Boy Scouts of America have proved contrived.
White House spokeswoman Sarah Huckabee Sanders confirmed there had been no calls.
But he said Trump wasn't lying.
Sanders said many of the scouts' leading figures spoke to Trump personally, and that Trump had spoken with Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto at the G20 meeting in Hamburg.
I wouldn't say it was a lie, that's a pretty tough accusation to make.
Those conversations happened, they didn't just happen on the phone but face to face," Sanders argued.
Speech to scouts sparked outcry
On Monday, Trump said the Mexican president had called him and praised Trump's success in rooting out illegal migration.
According to Trump, Pena Nieto said that few people come across the southern border of Mexico because they know that the trip will stop at the U.S. border anyway.
The Mexican government issued a statement Wednesday saying that no such call has taken place.
On Tuesday, Politico published a full version of Trump's interview with The Wall Street Journal.
In it, Trump enthused about his speech at a major meeting of the National Boy Scouts of America in West Virginia.
I got a call from the leader of the Boy Scouts, he said it was the finest speech ever given to them.
“They were very grateful,” Trump said.
On Wednesday, the Boy Scouts of America said it was not aware of a call from any of its executives to Trump.
According to the statement, an earlier statement by Michael Surbaugh, the head of the organization, in which he had apologized to the Boy Scouts for Trump's speech, speaks for itself.
Trump’s speech at the Boy Scouts of America meeting caused a lot of puzzlement, as it was exceptionally political given the nature of the event.
Among other things, he raved about the results of last fall's presidential election.
